								<h3><span style="color: #519DC7;">CALIPER: A Project of the Paediatric Focus Group of the CSCC</span></h3>
									<p>A Canadian team of investigators have assembled to lead the establishment of a reliable database<br>across the country. This national research initiative, working under the name of Canadian Laboratory<br>Initiative on Paediatric Reference Interval database (CALIPER database), is a key project of the<br>Paediatric Focus Group of the CSCC (Canadian Society of Clinical Chemists). The project has been<br>endorsed by the CSCC and the Research Ethics Board at several Canadian hospitals.
									</p>
								<h3><span style="color: #519DC7;">Study Population</span></h3>
									<p>The CALIPER study population will include both males and females comprising of six age groups as listed below:
									</p>
									<ul><li>Birth– 30 days</li>
										<li>1 month - 12 months</li>
										<li>1 - 5 years</li>
										<li>6 - 10 years</li>
										<li>11 - 14 years</li>
										<li>15 - 18 years</li>
									</ul>
								<table align="right" height="184" width="82">
									<tr><td style="padding: 10px;" rowspan="1" colspan="1"> 
										<img src="images/main_body/14621-wteen_boy.gif" alt="Caliper project teen boy " border="0" height="184" width="82" /> 
										</td>
									</tr>
								</table><p>Sample collection will be performed in various locations, depending on child’s age. They will include families<br>invited to SickKids or other study centers, as well as participating Gamma-Dynacare test centers. Applications<br>have also been submitted for collection in schools, daycares, community centers, and First Nation<br>communities.</p><table align="left" height="157" width="75" class="ie6fix"><tr><td style="padding: 10px;" rowspan="1" colspan="1">			
								<img src="images/main_body/14623-wgirl_green.gif" alt="Caliper project green girl" border="0" height="157" width="75" align="left" /> 
								</td></tr></table><h3><span style="color: #519DC7;">Benefits of CALIPER</span></h3><p>The major benefit of this project will be an accurate and reliable determination of what is<br>normal when a child is screened for a disease.</p><p>This in turn will contribute to better assessment and treatment of children in Canada<br>and internationally.</p><p>Furthermore, in addition to the inherent benefit of knowing one has helped sick children across the country<br>and the world, participants themselves (and/or family members or friends) could potentially be a patient<br>at SickKids or other paediatric health centre, and benefit directly from the results obtained from this study.</p><table align="right" height="224" width="75"><tr><td style="padding: 10px;" rowspan="1" colspan="1"> 
								<img src="images/main_body/14622-wteen_girl.gif" alt="Caliper project teen girl " border="0" height="224" width="75" /> 
								</td></tr></table><h3><span style="color: #519DC7;">Results</span></h3><p>All results will be anonymized. Personal information will remain strictly confidential.</p><p>The anonymized results of the study will be made available on the CALIPER website to allow for open<br>worldwide access. The data will also be published in reputable international journals. This wide<br>dissemination of the results is aimed to help with their use in children hospitals across Canada and worldwide,<br>as well as for purposes of public education.</p></p>
